```
Shortest distances from node 0:
  → Node 0: distance = 0,  path = 0
  → Node 1: distance = 4,  path = 0 → 1
  → Node 2: distance = 6,  path = 0 → 1 → 2
  → Node 3: distance = 7,  path = 0 → 1 → 2 →

# Dijkstra's Algorithm

## The Conceptual Map

Imagine you're lost in a city, and you want the *cheapest* route home — not just any route. You have a magical notebook where you write your **best known cost** to reach each intersection.

**The core insight:** Always explore the *cheapest unvisited place* next. Once you've visited somewhere, you've already found its optimal path — you can never do better by coming back to it later (assuming non-negative costs).

**The process — like ripples in a pond:**
1. Start at your source. Cost = 0. Everything else = ∞.
2. From your current position, *relax* each neighbor: "Could I reach you cheaper by going through me?"
3. Mark current node as visited (sealed — optimal path found).
4. Jump to the cheapest *unvisited* node. Repeat.
5. Stop when you reach your destination, or exhaust all nodes.

**The greedy guarantee:** Because all edge weights are non-negative, a cheaper path through an unvisited node can never "sneak up" and improve an already-sealed node.

---

## TypeScript Implementation

```typescript
// ─── Types ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

interface Edge {
  to: string;
  weight: number;
}

interface Graph {
  [node: string]: Edge[];
}

interface DijkstraResult {
  distances: Record<string, number>;
  previous: Record<string, string | null>;
  getPath: (target: string) => string[];
}

// ─── Min-Heap Priority Queue ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Using a proper heap gives us O((V + E) log V) instead of O(V²)

interface HeapNode {
  id: string;
  cost: number;
}

class MinHeap {
  private heap: HeapNode[] = [];

  get size() {
    return this.heap.length;
  }

  push(node: HeapNode): void {
    this.heap.push(node);
    this.bubbleUp(this.heap.length - 1);
  }

  pop(): HeapNode | undefined {
    if (this.heap.length === 0) return undefined;
    const min = this.heap[0];
    const last = this.heap.pop()!;
    if (this.heap.length > 0) {
      this.heap[0] = last;
      this.sinkDown(0);
    }
    return min;
  }

  private bubbleUp(i: number): void {
    while (i > 0) {
      const parent = Math.floor((i - 1) / 2);
      if (this.heap[parent].cost <= this.heap[i].cost) break;
      [this.heap[parent], this.heap[i]] = [this.heap[i], this.heap[parent]];
      i = parent;
    }
  }

  private sinkDown(i: number): void {
    const n = this.heap.length;
    while (true) {
      let smallest = i;
      const left = 2 * i + 1;
      const right = 2 * i + 2;

      if (left < n && this.heap[left].cost < this.heap[smallest].cost)
        smallest = left;
      if (right < n && this.heap[right].cost < this.heap[smallest].cost)
        smallest = right;
      if (smallest === i) break;

      [this.heap[smallest], this.heap[i]] = [this.heap[i], this.heap[smallest]];
      i = smallest;
    }
  }
}

// ─── Dijkstra's Algorithm ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

function dijkstra(graph: Graph, source: string): DijkstraResult {
  const distances: Record<string, number> = {};
  const previous: Record<string, string | null> = {};
  const visited = new Set<string>();
  const pq = new MinHeap();

  // Initialize — all distances unknown (∞), except the source
  for (const node in graph) {
    distances[node] = Infinity;
    previous[node] = null;
  }
  distances[source] = 0;
  pq.push({ id: source, cost: 0 });

  while (pq.size > 0) {
    const { id: current, cost } = pq.pop()!;

    // Skip if we already found a better path (stale heap entry)
    if (visited.has(current)) continue;
    visited.add(current);

    // Early exit if we somehow only need one target (optional optimization)
    // if (current === target) break;

    for (const { to: neighbor, weight } of graph[current] ?? []) {
      if (visited.has(neighbor)) continue;

      const newCost = cost + weight;

      // Relaxation — the heart of Dijkstra
      if (newCost < distances[neighbor]) {
        distances[neighbor] = newCost;
        previous[neighbor] = current;
        pq.push({ id: neighbor, cost: newCost }); // lazy deletion strategy
      }
    }
  }

  // Reconstruct path by walking backwards through 'previous'
  function getPath(target: string): string[] {
    const path: string[] = [];
    let current: string | null = target;

    while (current !== null) {
      path.unshift(current);
      current = previous[current] ?? null;
    }

    // If path doesn't start at source, no path exists
    return path[0] === source ? path : [];
  }

  return { distances, previous, getPath };
}

// ─── Example ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

const cityMap: Graph = {
  A: [{ to: "B", weight: 4 }, { to: "C", weight: 1 }],
  B: [{ to: "D", weight: 1 }],
  C: [{ to: "B", weight: 2 }, { to: "D", weight: 5 }],
  D: [{ to: "E", weight: 3 }],
  E: [],
};

const result = dijkstra(cityMap, "A");

console.log("Shortest distances from A:", result.distances);
// → { A: 0, B: 3, C: 1, D: 4, E: 7 }

console.log("Optimal path A → E:", result.getPath("E").join(" → "));
// → A → C → B → D → E

console.log("Optimal path A → D:", result.getPath("D").join(" → "));
// → A → C → B → D
```

---

## Complexity at a Glance

| With | Time | Space |
|------|------|-------|
| Min-Heap (this impl.) | `O((V + E) log V)` | `O(V + E)` |
| Naive array scan | `O(V²)` | `O(V)` |

**Min-heap wins on sparse graphs** (few edges). The naive version can win on dense graphs where `E ≈ V²`.

---

> *Dijkstra is greedy, but unlike most greedy algorithms, its greedy choice is provably optimal — because you can't travel negative distances in the real world. The moment Bellman-Ford enters the room (with negative edges), Dijkstra quietly leaves.*

# Dijkstra's Shortest Path Algorithm

## Conceptual Explanation

---

### The Core Problem
Given a weighted graph, find the shortest path from a **source node** to all other nodes (or a specific target node).

---

### The Mental Model: "Greedy Expansion"

Think of it like **dropping a stone in water** — ripples expand outward, always reaching closer shores before distant ones. Dijkstra guarantees we always process the *currently cheapest* unvisited node first.

---

### Key Invariant
> Once a node is **finalized** (visited), its shortest distance is **permanently known** and will never be updated.

This works because all edge weights must be **non-negative** — you can never find a cheaper path by going through a more expensive node first.

---

### Step-by-Step Mechanics

```
1. Initialize
   - dist[source] = 0
   - dist[all others] = ∞
   - visited = {}
   - priority queue = [(0, source)]

2. Loop until queue is empty:
   a. Pop node with MINIMUM distance (u)
   b. If u is already visited → skip
   c. Mark u as visited
   d. For each neighbor v of u:
      - newDist = dist[u] + weight(u, v)
      - If newDist < dist[v]:
          dist[v] = newDist
          prev[v] = u          ← track the path
          push (newDist, v) to queue

3. Result: dist[] contains shortest distances from source
           prev[] lets you reconstruct any path
```

---

### Visual Walkthrough

```
Graph:
    (A)--4--(B)
     |  \    |
     2   5   1
     |    \  |
    (C)--1--(D)

Source: A

Step 1: Queue=[(0,A)]  dist={A:0, B:∞, C:∞, D:∞}
Step 2: Pop A(0) → relax neighbors
        B: 0+4=4 ✓   C: 0+2=2 ✓   D: 0+5=5 ✓
        Queue=[(2,C),(4,B),(5,D)]

Step 3: Pop C(2) → relax neighbors
        A: 2+2=4 > 0, skip
        D: 2+1=3 < 5 ✓  update D!
        Queue=[(3,D),(4,B),(5,D)]

Step 4: Pop D(3) → relax neighbors
        B: 3+1=4 = 4, no improvement
        Queue=[(4,B),(5,D)]

Step 5: Pop B(4) → no improvements
Step 6: Pop D(5) → already visited, skip

Final: {A:0, B:4, C:2, D:3}
Path to B: A→C→D→B
```

---

### Complexity
| Structure | Time Complexity | Space |
|-----------|----------------|-------|
| Naive array | O(V²) | O(V) |
| Binary heap (typical) | O((V + E) log V) | O(V + E) |
| Fibonacci heap | O(E + V log V) | O(V + E) |

---

## TypeScript Implementation

```typescript
// ============================================================
// Types & Data Structures
// ============================================================

interface Edge {
  to: string;
  weight: number;
}

interface Graph {
  [node: string]: Edge[];
}

interface DijkstraResult {
  distances: Record<string, number>;
  previous: Record<string, string | null>;
  getPath: (target: string) => string[] | null;
}

// ============================================================
// Min-Heap Priority Queue
// (TypeScript stdlib has no built-in heap, so we implement one)
// ============================================================

interface HeapNode {
  node: string;
  distance: number;
}

class MinHeap {
  private heap: HeapNode[] = [];

  get size(): number {
    return this.heap.length;
  }

  isEmpty(): boolean {
    return this.heap.length === 0;
  }

  push(item: HeapNode): void {
    this.heap.push(item);
    this.bubbleUp(this.heap.length - 1);
  }

  pop(): HeapNode | undefined {
    if (this.isEmpty()) return undefined;

    const min = this.heap[0];
    const last = this.heap.pop()!;

    if (this.heap.length > 0) {
      this.heap[0] = last;
      this.sinkDown(0);
    }

    return min;
  }

  private bubbleUp(index: number): void {
    while (index > 0) {
      const parentIndex = Math.floor((index - 1) / 2);
      if (this.heap[parentIndex].distance <= this.heap[index].distance) break;

      [this.heap[parentIndex], this.heap[index]] =
        [this.heap[index], this.heap[parentIndex]];
      index = parentIndex;
    }
  }

  private sinkDown(index: number): void {
    const length = this.heap.length;

    while (true) {
      const left  = 2 * index + 1;
      const right = 2 * index + 2;
      let smallest = index;

      if (left < length && this.heap[left].distance < this.heap[smallest].distance) {
