**Complexity**: `get` and `put` are both **O(1)** time and **O(n)** space where n = capacity.

## LRU Cache in TypeScript — O(1) get & put

---

### Data Structure Choice

Achieving O(1) for both operations requires **two complementary structures**:

| Need | Structure |
|---|---|
| O(1) key lookup | `HashMap<key, node>` |
| O(1) eviction & recency tracking | Doubly-Linked List |

- **HashMap** gives instant node access by key — no scanning.
- **Doubly-Linked List** lets us move a node to the front (most-recent) or remove the tail (least-recent) in O(1), because we hold direct node references (not just values).
- A singly-linked list would require O(n) tail removal. An array/queue would be O(n) for arbitrary repositioning. This combo is the canonical solution.

---

### Implementation

```typescript
class DLinkedNode<K, V> {
  key: K | null;
  value: V | null;
  prev: DLinkedNode<K, V>;
  next: DLinkedNode<K, V>;

  constructor(key: K | null = null, value: V | null = null) {
    this.key = key;
    this.value = value;
    // prev/next assigned after construction
    this.prev = this as any;
    this.next = this as any;
  }
}

class LRUCache<K = number, V = number> {
  private capacity: number;
  private size: number;
  private map: Map<K, DLinkedNode<K, V>>;
  private head: DLinkedNode<K, V>; // dummy head (MRU side)
  private tail: DLinkedNode<K, V>; // dummy tail (LRU side)

  constructor(capacity: number) {
    if (capacity <= 0) throw new RangeError('Capacity must be a positive integer.');
    this.capacity = capacity;
    this.size = 0;
    this.map = new Map();

    // Sentinel nodes eliminate null checks on every insert/remove
    this.head = new DLinkedNode<K, V>();
    this.tail = new DLinkedNode<K, V>();
    this.head.next = this.tail;
    this.tail.prev = this.head;
  }

  // O(1) — returns value or -1 if absent
  get(key: K): V | -1 {
    const node = this.map.get(key);
    if (!node) return -1;
    this.moveToFront(node); // mark as most-recently used
    return node.value as V;
  }

  // O(1) — inserts or updates; evicts LRU entry when over capacity
  put(key: K, value: V): void {
    const existing = this.map.get(key);

    if (existing) {
      // Update value and promote to MRU
      existing.value = value;
      this.moveToFront(existing);
      return;
    }

    const node = new DLinkedNode(key, value);
    this.map.set(key, node);
    this.addToFront(node);
    this.size++;

    if (this.size > this.capacity) {
      const lru = this.removeTail();
      if (lru.key !== null) this.map.delete(lru.key);
      this.size--;
    }
  }

  // Optional utility
  get currentSize(): number { return this.size; }

  // ── Private helpers ──────────────────────────────────────────

  private addToFront(node: DLinkedNode<K, V>): void {
    node.prev = this.head;
    node.next = this.head.next;
    this.head.next.prev = node;
    this.head.next = node;
  }

  private removeNode(node: DLinkedNode<K, V>): void {
    node.prev.next = node.next;
    node.next.prev = node.prev;
  }

  private moveToFront(node: DLinkedNode<K, V>): void {
    this.removeNode(node);
    this.addToFront(node);
  }

  private removeTail(): DLinkedNode<K, V> {
    const lru = this.tail.prev;
    this.removeNode(lru);
    return lru;
  }
}
```

---

### Edge Cases Handled

| Scenario | Handling |
|---|---|
| `capacity <= 0` | Throws `RangeError` in constructor — invalid state. |
| `get` on missing key | Returns `-1` (LeetCode convention; change to `undefined` / `null` as needed). |
| `put` on existing key | Updates value **and** promotes node — no duplicate entries, no spurious eviction. |
| `put` on full cache | Evicts the LRU node (tail) **before** size overflows; `map.delete` keeps HashMap in sync. |
| `capacity = 1` | Works correctly — every `put` of a new key evicts the single existing entry. |
| Sentinel nodes | `head`/`tail` are dummy nodes, so `addToFront` and `removeTail` never dereference null pointers — no special-casing needed for empty-list states. |

