The standard O(1) LRU cache uses a `Map` + doubly-linked list, but JavaScript's `Map` preserves insertion order and exposes `keys().next()` for the oldest entry — making an explicit linked list unnecessary.

```typescript
class LRUCache<K, V> {
  private readonly capacity: number;
  private readonly cache: Map<K, V>;

  constructor(capacity: number) {
    if (capacity < 1) throw new RangeError("Capacity must be at least 1");
    this.capacity = capacity;
    this.cache = new Map();
  }

  get(key: K): V | undefined {
    if (!this.cache.has(key)) return undefined;
    // Promote to MRU position: delete then re-insert
    const value = this.cache.get(key)!;
    this.cache.delete(key);
    this.cache.set(key, value);
    return value;
  }

  put(key: K, value: V): void {
    if (this.cache.has(key)) {
      this.cache.delete(key);          // remove to refresh position
    } else if (this.cache.size >= this.capacity) {
      const lruKey = this.cache.keys().next().value!;
      this.cache.delete(lruKey);       // evict oldest entry
    }
    this.cache.set(key, value);        // insert as MRU
  }

  get size(): number { return this.cache.size; }
}
```

**Why `Map` alone works:** V8's `Map` is a hash table with O(1) get/set/delete, and it tracks insertion order. Re-inserting a key moves it to the end, so the first key is always the LRU. `keys().next()` is O(1) — it reads the head pointer of the internal linked list V8 maintains anyway.

**Edge cases handled:**

| Case | Behavior |
|------|----------|
| `get` on missing key | Returns `undefined` (not `-1`, because generics) |
| `put` on existing key | Deletes + re-inserts (refreshes recency, updates value) |
| Capacity = 0 | `RangeError` at construction time |
| Capacity = 1 | Every `put` evicts the previous entry |
| `put` when full | Evicts LRU before inserting new entry |

**When to use an explicit doubly-linked list instead:** If you need `O(1)` eviction *and* need to expose the LRU entry without deleting it, or if you're targeting an environment where `Map` order isn't guaranteed, an explicit `HashMap<K, Node<K,V>>` + doubly-linked list gives the same complexity with more control.

